9":"1129","1106":"1106","1037":"1037","1068":"1068","about 1037":"about 1037","Abt 1080":"about 1080","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Okehampton, Devon, England":"Okehampton, Devon, England","Cothercott, Shrop, England":"Cothercott, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Brionne, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Eure, Upper Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moels","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Moll  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Catalan: habitational name from any of various minor places called Moles, from the plural of <i>mola</i> (see   Mola  ).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Meulles (Calvados). See also   Moyles  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moll","meanings":["English (Norfolk): from the Middle English female personal name <i>Moll(e)</i>, <i>Mol</i>, a common pet form of <i>Maud</i> (see   Mould   and   Maude  ).","English (Norfolk): nickname from Middle English <i>molle</i>, <i>mol(e)</i>, <i>moul</i> ‘mole’ (the burrowing animal), given perhaps to someone who wore moleskin, a mole catcher, or to someone with poor sight, or alternatively from Middle English <i>mol</i> ‘effeminate man’.","German: nickname from a dialect term for a plump, stout person. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine) and Poland."]},{"name":"Mowles","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire): variant of   Moles  ."]}]},{"name":"Emme","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Emma  ,   Emily  , and related names, now used increasingly as an independent given name."],"variants":[{"name":"Emmy","meanings":["Pet form of   Emma  ,   Emily  , and related names, now used increasingly as an independent given name."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":29,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":49,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":59,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":69,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSum